edu.stanford.nlp.ie.util

Class RelationTriple

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.stanford.nlp.ie.util.RelationTriple
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Comparable<RelationTriple>, java.lang.Iterable<CoreLabel>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    RelationTriple.WithTree

    public class RelationTriple
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable<RelationTriple>, java.lang.Iterable<CoreLabel>
    A (subject, relation, object) triple; e.g., as used in the KBP challenges or in OpenIE systems.
    Author:
    Gabor Angeli

      • subject

        public final java.util.List<CoreLabel> subject
        The subject (first argument) of this triple

      • canonicalSubject

        public final java.util.List<CoreLabel> canonicalSubject
        The subject (first argument) of this triple, in its canonical mention (i.e., coref resolved)

      • relation

        public final java.util.List<CoreLabel> relation
        The relation (second argument) of this triple. Note that this is only the part of the relation that can be grounded in the sentence itself. Often, for a standalone readable relation string, you want to attach additional modifiers otherwise stored in the dependnecy arc. Therefore, for getting a String form of the relation, we recommend using relationGloss() or relationLemmaGloss().

      • object

        public final java.util.List<CoreLabel> object
        The object (third argument) of this triple

      • relationTokenSpan

        public Pair<java.lang.Integer,java.lang.Integer> relationTokenSpan()
        Get a representative span for the relation expressed by this triple. This is a bit more complicated than the subject and object spans, as the relation span is occasionally discontinuous. If this is the case, this method returns the largest contiguous chunk. If the relation span is empty, return the object span.

      • objectTokenSpan

        public Pair<java.lang.Integer,java.lang.Integer> objectTokenSpan()
        Gets the span of the NON-CANONICAL object.

      • isPrefixBe

        public boolean isPrefixBe()
        If true, this relation expresses a "to be" relation. For example, "President Obama" expresses the relation (Obama; be; President).

      • isPrefixBe

        public boolean isPrefixBe(boolean newValue)
        Set the value of this relation triple expressing a "to be" relation.
        Parameters:
        newValue - The new value of this relation being a "to be" relation.
        Returns:
        The old value of whether this relation expressed a "to be" relation.

      • isSuffixBe

        public boolean isSuffixBe()
        If true, this relation expresses a "to be" relation (with the be at the end of the sentence). For example, "Tim's father Tom" expresses the relation (Tim; 's father is; Tom).

      • isSuffixBe

        public boolean isSuffixBe(boolean newValue)
        Set the value of this relation triple expressing a "to be" relation (suffix).
        Parameters:
        newValue - The new value of this relation being a "to be" relation.
        Returns:
        The old value of whether this relation expressed a "to be" relation.

      • isSuffixOf

        public boolean isSuffixOf()
        If true, this relation has an ungrounded "of" at the end of the relation. For example, "United States president Barack Obama" expresses the relation (Obama; is president of; United States).

      • isSuffixOf

        public boolean isSuffixOf(boolean newValue)
        Set the value of this triple missing an ungrounded "of" in the relation string.
        Parameters:
        newValue - The new value of this relation missing an "of".
        Returns:
        The old value of whether this relation missing an "of".

      • istmod

        public boolean istmod()
        If true, this relation expresses a tmod (temporal modifier) relation that is not grounded in the sentence. For example, "I went to the store Friday" would otherwise yield a strange triple (I; go to store; Friday).

      • istmod

        Returns:
